        <h2 id="examples">Real on-page SEO examples</h2>

        <h3>1. Local plumber — page 5 to page 1 without backlinks</h3>
        <p>A drain cleaning service page had no H1, no keyword in the title, 4 sentences of content, and a generic meta description. After optimisation — keyword-rich title, clear H1, 800 words of helpful content, and internal links — rankings jumped from page 5 to page 1 within 6 weeks. No new backlinks were built.</p>

        <h3>2. SaaS company — 40% traffic increase from the same content</h3>
        <p>A B2B software blog published 10 posts per month but used identical meta description templates, non-optimised H1s, and zero internal links. After an audit and targeted fixes — unique title and meta tags per post, keyword-optimised headings, internal linking — organic traffic increased 40% in 3 months without publishing a single new post.</p>

        <h3>3. Ecommerce — long-tail rankings from title tag fixes</h3>
        <p>An online retailer had 500 product pages using the same title template: "Buy [Product] | Store Name." After creating unique, descriptive titles with specific attributes (size, colour, material), individual pages began ranking for long-tail queries that previously returned zero impressions in Google Search Console.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">On-page SEO vs. off-page SEO — what to prioritise first</h2>
        <p>Both are necessary. The question is sequencing. On-page first — always.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>On-page SEO</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Full control — no external dependencies</li>
              <li>Results in days to weeks</li>
              <li>Low risk — changes are reversible</li>
              <li>Foundation for everything else</li>
              <li>Start here before any link building</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Off-page SEO</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Depends on third-party sites</li>
              <li>Results in months</li>
              <li>Higher risk — bad tactics cause penalties</li>
              <li>Amplifies on-page work</li>
              <li>Only effective once on-page is solid</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">8 on-page SEO best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>One primary keyword per page.</strong> Place it in the title tag, H1, URL slug, and the first 100 words of body copy.</li>
          <li><strong>Write for search intent, not keyword density.</strong> Informational queries need explanations and examples. Commercial queries need comparisons and CTAs. Match the format to the intent.</li>
          <li><strong>Keep title tags under 60 characters.</strong> Google truncates longer titles in search results, often cutting off the keyword.</li>
          <li><strong>Use descriptive H2s as questions.</strong> Question-format H2s target People Also Ask boxes and increase featured-snippet eligibility.</li>
          <li><strong>Optimise every image with descriptive alt text.</strong> Include the keyword where it genuinely fits. Alt text also serves as accessibility copy for screen readers.</li>
          <li><strong>Link internally from high-authority pages.</strong> Every new page should receive at least one internal link from a page that already ranks or has backlinks.</li>
          <li><strong>Update thin content rather than create new content.</strong> Expanding a 300-word page to 1,200 words is faster and lower-risk than publishing from scratch — and often produces stronger ranking lifts.</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor rankings after changes.</strong> Use Google Search Console to track position changes for target keywords within 2–4 weeks of any on-page edit.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — keyword stuffing</div>
          <p>Inserting the primary keyword 15–20 times in 500 words is keyword stuffing. Google's algorithms detect unnatural repetition and may apply a manual penalty. Target natural keyword density (1–2% of body words) and use semantic variations to cover the topic thoroughly.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common on-page SEO mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Duplicate title tags</strong> — each page needs a unique title. Duplicates confuse Google about which page to rank for a query.</li>
          <li><strong>Missing H1 or multiple H1s</strong> — every page needs exactly one H1 that matches the primary keyword.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring meta descriptions</strong> — not a direct ranking factor, but a weak or missing description hurts click-through rate and wastes prime search-result real estate.</li>
          <li><strong>No internal links to new pages</strong> — Google can't rank a page it can't find. Always add at least one internal link when publishing.</li>
          <li><strong>Optimising for keywords without checking intent</strong> — ranking for a keyword with the wrong content format (a blog post when searchers want a product page) drives zero conversions.</li>
          <li><strong>Treating on-page SEO as one-time setup</strong> — content decays. Competitors update their pages. Refresh top-ranking pages every 6–12 months.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
